Well, I hung the other nesting box during the day. Here's how it looks in a good spot in the garden.
But, a little flash-back: "What's inside?", don't I hear ask.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I scavenged from a Raspberry Pi device.
Since this plastic box has an odd shape, it's due to the pivoting side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like this and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
As there is no electricity in the garden, the entire system is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 cell with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of energy.
I call that a feature. So the birds can also have a bit of privacy.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the Internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points that I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and point it downwards towards the garden.
I could still do it when I install more camera nest boxes, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
